rrection, which continues to shape policing of protest and surveillance, notably in response to the Black Lives Matter movement. Ultimately, Passavant argues, this trend of violent policing strategies against protesters is evidence of the emergence of a post-democratic state in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAuthoritarianismxHistoryy21st century. 0aBlack lives matter movement. 0aMilitarization of policezUnited States. 0aNeoliberalismxHistoryy21st century. 0aOccupy movementzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aPolice brutalityzUnited States. 0aPolicezUnited States. 0aProtest movementsxHistoryy21st centuryzUnited States. 0aProtest movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478013013zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478013013423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478013013/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles